Histology Lab
1. What is the general tissue type?
2. What is the specific tissue type?
3. Give an example of a location in the body where you would find this tissue type? Learn 1
or 2 and be able to give them as an example.
4. What cellular characteristic is this pointing to (ie- apical surface, basement membrane…)?


Epithelial Tissue
Specific Epithelial Tissues
1. Simple Squamous Epithelium
  a. Location - alveoli of lungs; outside lining of GI tract
  b. Cellular characteristics - nucleus
2. Simple Cuboidal Epithelium
  a. Location - kidney tubules; inside lining of ducts
  b. Cellular characteristics - lumen, apical surface, nucleus, basement membrane
3. Simple Columnar Epithelium
  a. Location - inside lining of intestine; inside lining of stomach
  b. Cellular characteristics - lumen, apical surface, nucleus, basement membrane
  c. Goblet cells - produce mucus
4. Nonkeratinized Stratified Squamous Epithelium
  a. Location - inside lining of esophagus; inside lining of mouth; inside lining of vagina
  b. Cellular characteristics - lumen, basement membrane, apical surface, germinal layer
5. Keratinized Stratified Squamous Epithelium (we will go into MUCH more detail in the skin
section)
  a. Location - epidermis
  b. Cellular characteristics - keratinized layer, germinal layer, apical surface
6. Transitional Epithelium
  a. Location - inside lining of ureters; inside lining of bladder
  b. Cellular characteristics - lumen, apical surface, basement membrane
7. Ciliated Pseudostratified columnar Epithelium
  a. Location - inside lining of trachea; male urethra; epididymis
  b. Cellular characteristics - lumen, cilia, basement membrane


Connective Tissue
Specific Connective Tissue to know:
1. Areolar connective tissue
  a. Location - subcutaneous layer
  b. Cellular characteristics - fibroblast, collagen fiber, elastic fiber
2. Adipose tissue
  a. Location - subcutaneous layer; surrounding organs; behind eyes
  b. Cellular characteristics - oil droplet, nucleus, cytoplasm
3. Dense regular connective tissue
  a. Location - tendons; ligaments
  b. Cellular characteristics - collagen fibers, fibroblast nuclei
4. Dense irregular connective tissue
  a. Location - dermis; white of the eye (sclera)
  b. Cellular characteristics - collagen fibers, fibroblast nuclei
5. Hyaline cartilage
  a. Location - epiphyseal plate; tracheal rings; articular cartilage; nose
  b. Cellular characteristics - perichondrium, chondroblast, chondrocyte, lacunae; matrix (predominantly collagen fibers)
6. Elastic cartilage
  a. Location - ear; epiglottis; eustachian tube
  b. Cellular characteristics - perichondrium, chondroblast, chondrocyte, lacunae; matrix (predominantly elastic fibers)
7. Bone
  a. Location - bone
  b. Cellular characteristics - osteon; central canal; concentric lamella; interstitial lamella;
  osteocyte; osteoblast; lacuna; canaliculi; perforating canal; periosteum; spongy bone
  (model only); endosteum (model only)
NOTE: Matrix is made up of ground substance and fibers. There are three fiber types: collagen fibers, elastic
fibers, reticular fibers

Muscle
Be able to list the major characteristics of the 3 different types of muscle tissue.
1. Skeletal muscle
  a. Shape - rod shaped
  b. Number of nuclei - multiple
  c. Striated
  d. Voluntary
2. Smooth muscle
  a. Shape - spindle shaped
  b. Number of nuclei - one
  c. Non-striated
  d. Involuntary
3. Cardiac muscle
  a. Shape - branched
  b. Number of nuclei - one
  c. Striated
  d. Involuntary



Specific Tissue Type
1. Skeletal Muscle
  a. Location - muscles of the body
  b. Cellular characteristics - nuclei, striations, sarcolemma, endomysium, perimysium, fascicles,
epimysium
2. Smooth Muscle
  a. Location - Walls of the GI tract, walls of blood vessels, uterus
  b. Cellular characteristics - nuclei, endomysium
3. Cardiac Muscle
  a. Location - heart
  b. Cellular characteristics - nuclei, striations, intercalated disc (desmosomes and gap junctions)



Nervous Tissue
Be able to list the two types of cells that make up nervous tissue


Skin Lab
1. Be able to list the 2 major layers and the primary tissue that composes each.
    a. Epidermis - keratinized stratified squamous epithelium
    b. Dermis - 20% areolar connective tissue and 80% dense irregular connective tissue

2. Be able to identify the different layers of the epidermis in both thick and thin skin.
    a. Stratum basale
    b. Stratum spinosum
    c. Stratum granulosum
    d. Stratum lucidum (only in thick skin)
    e. Stratum corneum
3. Be able to identify the different layers of the dermis.
    a. Papillary region
    b. Reticular region
4. Be able to locate and identify the following on models and slide:
    ● dermal papillae
    ● sebaceous glands
    ● Hair shaft
    ● hair follicle
    ● Hair root
    ● Papillae of hair
    ● sweat glands
    ● Sweat gland duct
    ● arrector pili muscles
    ● pacinian corpuscles
    ● meissner's corpuscles
